Boil a #kettle{} of @water{800%ml}. Finely slice the @spring onion{3} widthways into ½cm discs, separating the white from the green parts. Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{} if you have one). Peel the @ginger{1%thumb-sized piece} using the edge of a #spoon{} and then grate or chop very finely. Chop the @coriander{1%bunch}(chopped).

Heat a splash of @oil{} on medium heat in a large #frying pan{}. Add the whites of your spring onion, your garlic and your ginger. After ~{1%minute} add the @red Thai style paste{2%tsp} and stir.

> If you are sensitive to spice add a bit less!

After another ~{1%minute} add the @coconut milk{400%ml} and stir until smooth. Add the @chicken stock pot{1} with the boiling water from your kettle and bring to a simmer. This is the base of your laksa!

Add the @kaffir lime leaf{2}, the @peanut butter{3%tbsp} and @?sugar{pinch}. Roll the @lime{1} firmly between the flat of your hand and the work surface. Once you've loosened it up, cut it in half and squeeze the lime juice into your laksa. Simmer gently for ~{10%minutes}.

Meanwhile, trim any fatty bits from the @British chicken thighs{6}. Heat a splash of @oil{} in a #nonstick frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Once hot, add your chicken and cook for around ~{4%minutes} on each side then remove.

> Your chicken is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

After 10 mins add the @egg noodle nest{4} to your laksa and cook for around ~{4%minutes}, or until your egg noodles are soft enough to eat.

Lastly, thinly slice your chicken and add it to your laksa. Serve into big #bowls{} with a topping of your coriander and the greens of your spring onion.